WEBVTT

00:06.050 --> 00:13.761
If God comes to you and wants to love you to the infinite degree, He has to seek your praise.

00:15.544 --> 00:23.795
Because your delight in Him as your treasure comes to consummation in expressions of praise to Him.

00:25.418 --> 00:33.970
And therefore He's the one being in the universe for whom self-aggrandizement is the highest virtue, is the most loving thing to do.

00:35.842 --> 00:43.395
I think most of us instinctively recoil at the idea that someone would be all about their own praise.

00:44.236 --> 00:50.567
But John Piper shows us here why, with God, it's actually the most loving thing possible.

00:51.508 --> 00:52.230
I'm Dan Kruver.

00:52.871 --> 01:01.906
In this episode of Light and Truth, John Piper helps us see why God's glory and our joy actually belong together.

01:02.498 --> 01:09.088
The seminar was originally delivered at Bethlehem Baptist Church on Wednesday evening, November 13, 1991.

01:13.835 --> 01:14.916
Let me pose a question.

01:15.577 --> 01:18.842
Like me, you would be troubled by this question now.

01:19.423 --> 01:29.778
Namely, if you say God is a show-off or if you say He loves His reputation or if you say He has a passionate zeal to become famous

01:30.626 --> 01:36.933
There's something inside us that says, yeah, but we're not supposed to do that.

01:37.694 --> 01:40.196
So how come God's supposed to do that?

01:40.717 --> 01:41.918
I don't like it.

01:42.859 --> 01:58.336
There's a gut reaction until you've got all the pieces in place that make you say, that doesn't sound like the kind of John 3 16 God I learned about in Sunday school.

01:58.356 --> 02:00.018
Or to sum it up, it doesn't sound like

02:00.226 --> 02:01.087
God is loving.

02:01.107 --> 02:03.771
He's so wrapped up in self.

02:05.454 --> 02:12.725
Now, let me try to answer that in a nutshell here before moving on.

02:12.745 --> 02:19.875
And those of you who've read Desiring God, I hope would be able to reproduce this argument, but it's really crucial.

02:21.177 --> 02:23.721
God is unique in the universe.

02:23.941 --> 02:26.044
Nobody is like God.

02:26.405 --> 02:29.810
He is totally self-sufficient and needs

02:30.178 --> 02:30.879
Nobody.

02:31.781 --> 02:32.863
We are not like that.

02:33.043 --> 02:33.884
We are needy.

02:34.005 --> 02:35.087
We are deficient.

02:35.127 --> 02:35.868
We are sinners.

02:35.948 --> 02:36.789
We are finite.

02:36.830 --> 02:37.571
We are weak.

02:38.112 --> 02:40.796
We are utterly unlike God in that regard.

02:41.658 --> 02:46.486
And therefore it may be that right for God to do some things is not right for us to do.

02:49.632 --> 02:54.280
And love on God's part might look like something that love on our part doesn't look like.

02:54.580 --> 02:55.602
If I

02:55.970 --> 03:05.144
were to go about the world saying, my goal is to become famous, my goal is to attract attention to myself, my goal is to magnify my glory.

03:05.724 --> 03:17.341
I think you would be absolutely right in saying that man is a megalomaniac, he's conceited, he's egocentric, he's not loving, because all he is cares about himself.

03:17.922 --> 03:22.209
He doesn't really care about us, because attracting us to him, what's that?

03:23.591 --> 03:25.874
Now, if you go up to God,

03:27.202 --> 03:35.472
and picture God doing that, can you account for why that would be loving?

03:35.492 --> 03:52.534
For God to go around the world saying, I want your praise, I want your glory, I want your honor, I want to be famous among you, I want to have a good reputation, I want to be known by you, I want everybody's praise and glory for myself.

03:53.355 --> 03:54.276
Why would that be loving?

03:54.857 --> 03:55.698
And here's the reason.

03:57.986 --> 04:02.190
When you love somebody, what you give to them is what's best.

04:04.652 --> 04:07.235
And the best thing God can give is God.

04:08.396 --> 04:11.599
If he were to give us the world and not himself, he would not be loving.

04:12.420 --> 04:20.528
So God is loving in giving me himself as a treasure that I find buried in a field.

04:20.568 --> 04:25.432
And in my joy, I go and sell everything I have to buy that field because he is my treasure.

04:25.773 --> 04:27.314
And so he gives himself to me.

04:28.002 --> 04:28.563
Then C.S.

04:28.603 --> 04:38.578
Lewis taught me, what do you do when you receive something that is of paramount importance and excellence in the world?

04:39.319 --> 04:43.805
Answer, you praise it, you talk about it, you exalt it.

04:44.647 --> 04:57.746
And what Lewis taught me, and this is so liberating, is that the joy that you have in your treasure is consummated by the release of

04:58.018 --> 05:03.104
of words and expressions of appreciation and value that's on it.

05:04.145 --> 05:05.747
You all had experiences like that.

05:06.848 --> 05:08.450
The most recent one would be at the dome.

05:09.411 --> 05:11.153
That's the biggest one would be at the dome.

05:11.453 --> 05:21.344
Seventh game, suppose that you're allowed to go in there, and as you go in to the seventh game of the World Series, they're handing out these little cards.

05:21.684 --> 05:26.269
And on the card is written, Dear Ladies and Gentlemen.

05:26.289 --> 05:26.770
Tonight,

05:27.234 --> 05:33.803
We would like you to have maximum joy in the twins, our treasured ball team.

05:34.604 --> 05:42.055
And you may experience pleasure to the maximum of your potential of joy tonight.

05:42.676 --> 05:45.499
There is just one qualification.

05:46.321 --> 05:49.064
No sound may come out of your mouth.

05:50.126 --> 05:55.954
Now, I don't think it's true that you would say, well, no problem.

05:56.194 --> 06:00.641
we could all experience maximum joy, we just wouldn't be able to express it.

06:02.144 --> 06:10.878
That's not true, because the expression of those crazy fans is the consummation of a joy.

06:11.198 --> 06:20.513
If you hold their hands down, if you hold their shoulders down, your mouth, you are cutting joy off at a certain level and not letting it come to completion.

06:21.675 --> 06:23.698
Now, if that's true and Lewis

06:23.970 --> 06:53.714
documents it from all kinds of things quite forget baseball and talk about whatever you love if if you love something really are emotionally engaged with it and you are forbidden from any kind of demonstration or expression of that value then your joy does not come to consummation in that thing if that's true then God is seeking the consummation of your joy in seeking

06:54.562 --> 06:55.203
your praise.

06:58.869 --> 07:03.176
He's the only being in the universe that can do that without being unloving.

07:03.897 --> 07:11.449
If I were to seek your praise for me and not for God, I would be seeking your loss.

07:12.891 --> 07:14.534
I wouldn't be seeking your ultimate joy.

07:15.095 --> 07:22.226
But if I'm God, let's just say if God comes to you and wants to love you to the infinite degree

07:23.330 --> 07:34.965
He has to seek your praise because your delight in him as your treasure comes to consummation in expressions of praise to him.

07:36.607 --> 07:45.118
And therefore, he's the one being in the universe for whom self-aggrandizement is the highest virtue, is the most loving thing to do.

07:45.138 --> 07:45.819
Let me say that again.

07:46.160 --> 07:51.186
He's the one being in the universe for whom self-exaltation

07:51.682 --> 07:53.665
is the most loving thing he can do.

07:55.127 --> 07:56.448
You can't copy him in that.

07:58.792 --> 08:07.203
To copy him in that is to say that the most loving thing you can do is to live for God's exaltation.

08:07.223 --> 08:07.764
Not your own.

08:08.384 --> 08:09.486
Then you really copy him.

08:09.786 --> 08:11.348
He lives for God exaltation.

08:11.769 --> 08:13.451
We ought to live for God's exaltation.

08:13.551 --> 08:18.578
And since exalting God brings our joy to consummation,

08:19.170 --> 08:22.214
Therefore, it is a loving thing for God to be self-centered.

08:25.299 --> 08:31.548
Or God is most glorified in you when you are most satisfied in Him.

08:31.568 --> 08:34.792
We just unpacking Christian hedonism here.

08:36.455 --> 08:47.250
I want you to be able to handle that because I know that when I say these kinds of things and we just have a whole slew of texts more to look at, unless you can process

08:48.450 --> 08:51.053
how this is loving, it just won't sound right.

08:53.677 --> 09:02.288
The fear that I have is that we have construed the love of God in a very man-centered way.

09:04.031 --> 09:06.654
And what I've just presented to you is a safeguard.

09:06.734 --> 09:15.506
It's a theological, biblical safeguard against interpreting the love of God for you in a you-centered way.

09:17.826 --> 09:20.729
God loves me for his glory.

09:22.851 --> 09:46.674
Remember what it says in Romans 15, seven, and eight, I think it says, Christ became a servant to the circumcision to show the truthfulness of God in order that he might confirm the promises to the patriarchs and in order that the Gentiles and Minneapolis might

09:47.106 --> 09:50.892
glorify Him for His mercy.

09:53.836 --> 10:04.752
Christ became a servant, that is He became incarnate, and lived, and suffered, and died in a Jewish context in order that Minneapolis Gentiles might glorify Him for mercy.

10:05.594 --> 10:08.298
He loved us for the glory of His mercy.

10:10.321 --> 10:11.282
And unless you

10:11.426 --> 10:17.014
Unless you compute the love of God that way, you will put yourself at the center of God's universe.

10:18.416 --> 10:20.759
That's what a lot of people do with John 3 16.

10:25.025 --> 10:32.696
And God belongs at the center of his universe, and I'm real happy to drink at the edges of that fountain forever.

10:34.899 --> 10:35.700
Now, where are we?

10:36.521 --> 10:40.146
Let's keep going with question number

10:41.762 --> 10:50.833
Well, just a couple more texts to answer question number six about the name of God and the reputation of God.

10:52.755 --> 11:04.770
Isaiah 43, 20, God calls the people of Israel, those whom I formed for myself that they might declare my praise.

11:06.192 --> 11:10.216
So he chose Israel that they might declare his praise.

11:10.276 --> 11:11.538
That's why Israel existed.

11:11.778 --> 11:15.243
Now, here we are in the New Testament, 1 Peter 2, 9.

11:15.823 --> 11:16.324
Same thing.

11:17.265 --> 11:25.376
You, speaking to the church, are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, God's own people.

11:25.657 --> 11:26.037
Why?

11:26.578 --> 11:28.240
Why did he choose Bethlehem?

11:28.580 --> 11:31.104
All those in Bethlehem who are his.

11:32.786 --> 11:39.795
That you may declare the wonderful deeds of him who called you out of darkness into his marvelous light.

11:40.416 --> 11:41.778
We exist

11:41.922 --> 11:44.004
to make a name for God.

11:47.968 --> 11:57.419
I was just writing a letter this afternoon to one of our staff, and it's his birthday tomorrow.

11:58.460 --> 11:59.040
It's Tom.

12:00.702 --> 12:11.794
And as I was writing, Tom and I have been working together now for 11 years.

12:12.866 --> 12:15.390
tremendously precious partner in the ministry.

12:16.371 --> 12:23.201
And I got carried away about my own sense of call.

12:24.242 --> 12:38.482
And I said, Tom, it's becoming simpler and clearer in these days that I just feel like my life is to be spent upholding the godness of God.

12:40.354 --> 12:54.750
just putting God on the agenda of people's lives, reasserting God's place in the areas of life, declaring that God is the centerpiece, that God is the center of his own affections.

12:54.930 --> 13:09.426
Just God, God, God, America, God, Bethlehem, God, evangelicalism, not man, not techniques, not management, not programs, not causes,

13:09.634 --> 13:12.298
But God, God, God.

13:12.799 --> 13:16.444
This is sort of a simple way of defining my path of significance.

13:19.488 --> 13:20.029
And there it is.

13:20.089 --> 13:23.474
It'll be different.

13:24.215 --> 13:25.858
The path will be different for each of us.

13:25.938 --> 13:34.450
But all of us really ought to say that the essence of my life is to image forth God for people.

13:36.258 --> 13:58.723
Declare the wonderful deeds of him who called you out of darkness into his marvelous light Question number seven According to 2 Samuel 7 23 What is the unique thing about Israel?

14:00.665 --> 14:05.010
By implication, what's the unique thing today?

14:06.242 --> 14:08.684
about being God's people.

14:09.665 --> 14:34.930
2 Samuel 7, 23 says, What other nation on earth is like your people Israel whom God went to redeem to be his people making a name for himself and doing for them great and terrible things by driving out before his people a nation

14:35.042 --> 14:36.083
And it's God's.

14:38.045 --> 14:41.849
My question was, what's the unique thing about Israel?

14:42.309 --> 14:48.515
And the answer is, the unique thing about us or Israel is not us.

14:50.237 --> 14:52.859
The unique thing about Israel is not Israel.

14:54.201 --> 14:57.964
It's God's making himself a name by what he does with us.

14:59.586 --> 15:03.730
The unique thing about God's people is that they are the

15:04.098 --> 15:14.591
freely unconditionally chosen showcase for his making a name for himself in a whole bunch of ways and that's what unique about us.

15:14.832 --> 15:22.381
God chose to make a name for himself on this person or on this church or on this people.

15:22.401 --> 15:25.745
It's a very humbling effect if you understand it at its root.

15:28.729 --> 15:32.594
You know, I feel like I should insert this here just by way of caution.

15:32.706 --> 15:36.651
with regard to the issue of pride and boasting theologically.

15:39.714 --> 15:47.083
I would like it to be true that there were a theology that is so humbling you can't boast in it.

15:49.366 --> 15:50.247
That's not true.

15:51.509 --> 15:52.890
There is no such theology.

15:54.452 --> 16:02.482
There is a humbling theology, it's called biblical theology, that if you properly respond to it and understand it humbles you.

16:03.874 --> 16:11.044
But you know what taught me that there is no theology that you can't brag about and use as a ground for boasting?

16:11.985 --> 16:15.890
It's by just looking at the sorts of things people do boast about in society.

16:16.932 --> 16:21.137
For example, people actually boast about being white.

16:24.682 --> 16:27.706
Now tell me, what did any white person do to get white?

16:30.770 --> 16:33.714
Zero, absolutely zero.

16:34.082 --> 16:37.426
Nothing, I mean nothing, less than nothing.

16:39.208 --> 16:46.055
How can you possibly boast in something for which you did less than nothing to become?

16:48.518 --> 16:51.641
But we can, we can, we do it.

16:53.803 --> 17:03.794
Or American, or a piper, or Jones or Smith, or, I mean, there's a whole array

17:03.970 --> 17:13.384
of characteristics which you have, which you have absolutely nothing to do with, which you are tempted to brag about and feel superior about.

17:13.404 --> 17:16.368
And you have nothing to do with it.

17:17.770 --> 17:27.645
Sheer, I mean, I've often said the most clear demonstration of unconditional grace in my life is that I was born in the family of Bill and Ruth Piper.

17:29.207 --> 17:30.790
Absolutely nothing to do with it.

17:31.811 --> 17:33.714
I could have been born into a Muslim family.

17:37.186 --> 17:45.115
Now, I just say that to say, I'm right now saying this is a humbling theology I'm giving you, but I'm not naive.

17:45.135 --> 17:51.161
I know that you could walk out of here and go down the street and brag that tonight you learned how to be humble.

17:51.602 --> 17:52.262
You could do that.

17:53.364 --> 17:54.985
It is a humbling thing, however.

17:55.366 --> 18:06.578
It's a humbling thing to be told that the unique thing about you is that God freely chose you to make a showcase for his power, his glory, his excellence, his virtue, and you just happened to be

18:06.754 --> 18:12.242
the clay on which he is demonstrating his remarkable skill.

18:13.864 --> 18:29.006
We've already looked at question number eight about the work of God at the Red Sea, the ultimate aim of God in the Exodus, and how was the missionary effectiveness of this aim illustrated in the following history.

18:29.507 --> 18:32.891
He divided the sea to demonstrate his glory and Rahab.

18:33.332 --> 18:33.913
Heard about it.

18:34.153 --> 18:34.674
She was

18:34.914 --> 18:46.151
converted, it says in Hebrews 11 that she was the woman of faith and therefore his interest in his name also became a means of salvation.

18:47.774 --> 19:00.293
Number nine, using Psalm 106 verses 7 and 8, explain what I mean by gospel logic.

19:00.314 --> 19:03.218
How does this passage show that

19:03.362 --> 19:08.308
God's God's centeredness is the ground of the gospel.

19:09.029 --> 19:11.131
Psalm 106, seven through eight.

19:13.634 --> 19:18.820
Our fathers, when they were in Egypt, did not consider thy wonderful works.

19:19.561 --> 19:27.050
They did not remember the abundance of thy steadfast love, but rebelled against the most high at the Red Sea.

19:27.430 --> 19:30.834
So God is not rescuing a very cooperative people here.

19:33.026 --> 19:36.852
He's not their virtue that's eliciting his mercy and power.

19:40.156 --> 19:52.755
Yet, this is the gospel yet now, yet he saved them for his namesake that he might make known his mighty power.

19:54.337 --> 19:56.500
Now here's what I mean by gospel logic.

19:59.524 --> 20:00.626
Salvation

20:01.762 --> 20:05.748
is grounded not in my virtue.

20:05.808 --> 20:10.155
It's not grounded in my accomplishments.

20:11.036 --> 20:22.354
It's grounded ultimately in God's zeal to uphold his name and demonstrate his mighty power in my life.

20:30.114 --> 20:40.329
so that we pray things like, for thy namesake, O Lord, pardon my guilt, for it is great.

20:44.315 --> 20:49.503
One of my goals is that you would understand that prayer and pray it from now on.

20:51.126 --> 20:56.594
That when you bow to pray, you would pray, my guilt is great,

20:59.042 --> 21:00.063
Please forgive it.

21:01.706 --> 21:02.026
Why?

21:02.046 --> 21:07.593
For your name is at stake in my forgiveness.

21:08.855 --> 21:22.814
Now we've got lots more to say about that because we must get the New Testament here and the cross and how the blood of Jesus is in fact a demonstration of the worth of the name of God.

21:25.818 --> 21:29.042
When you pray, hallowed be thy name.

21:30.690 --> 21:31.931
Close your prayers.

21:33.413 --> 21:38.098
I'm troubled when people don't close their prayers in Jesus' name.

21:38.118 --> 21:51.854
I hesitate to say anything the first or second or third or fourth or fifth time because I don't want to be picky about what you have to say out loud and what you have to think in your head.

21:53.356 --> 21:59.122
But after a pattern develops and people don't pray in Jesus' name, get real concerned.

21:59.746 --> 22:02.911
that maybe they really don't understand what's going on here.

22:05.475 --> 22:25.385
Because what's going on in putting hallowed be thy name at the beginning and in Jesus name, amen at the end is a statement that the goal of my prayer in my life and the universe is the hallowing, the magnifying, the cherishing, the praising of God's glorious name.

22:26.386 --> 22:29.010
And the ground of all my hope

22:29.346 --> 22:39.839
that anything I've prayed now would be answered to that end is God's love for the name of His Son, which was vindicated and demonstrated in the cross.

22:41.841 --> 22:48.129
For me to say in Jesus' name, amen, at the end of a prayer is no throwaway phrase.

22:49.651 --> 22:55.378
It's a statement of absolute reliance upon what Jesus did on the cross.

22:55.682 --> 22:59.968
I have no claim to get any prayer answered at all as a sinner.

23:00.389 --> 23:04.535
Zero, I have no access whatsoever into the throne room.

23:05.496 --> 23:23.602
I am dirty and defiled and outside, and God in His freedom said His favor upon me, and for Jesus' sake cleansed me, and what I mean by for Jesus' sake is that in Jesus the name of God was vindicated in saving those who trust in Him.

23:23.970 --> 23:29.195
So when I say in Jesus' name, I mean, He did it all.

23:29.836 --> 23:31.818
Everything is based on Jesus.

23:32.758 --> 23:41.847
Every little echo of my desire for hope and for help and for my children and my marriage and my church, it's all on Jesus.

23:43.949 --> 23:52.978
Thank you for listening to this episode of Light and Truth, where we are committed to providing God-centered preaching to help you see Christ clearly,

23:53.122 --> 23:54.545
and treasure him truly.

23:55.246 --> 23:56.729
I'm your host, Dan Kruver.

23:57.731 --> 24:06.630
On our next episode, John Piper begins an eight-part series titled, Living and Dying for the Glory of Christ.

24:07.351 --> 24:08.153
I hope you'll join us.

24:09.215 --> 24:12.722
